You can go north or out.

You are in your own home. It is still a modest (i.e. rather too small) town house, which is in a rather chaotic state as you try to prepare for Christmas. The floor is strewn with Amazon delivery boxes. On the wall is an advent calendar with an alarming amount of doors already open.

Just like last year you've left things a bit late and are missing the following essential items for a decent Christmas: Logs for the Fire, A Selection of Cheese, Chestnuts, Some Wrapping Paper,  Sniper Elite 4 Computer Game,a Bottle of Port and a copy of the Bumper Radio Times Christmas Special. You'd better head out into town to get some shopping done, problem is that you've run out of money. Perhaps there are other ways to get what you need.

 (type 'game' for game specific help)

> out

> out

You are in Chester Street.

You can go in, east or west.

You are outside Your House on a side road near the city centre, that runs from East to West.

The daylight is waning and there is a strange looking star in the western sky.

It's crisp and cold, and in the distance you can hear carol singing.

> x star

> x star

In the western sky you see a faintly glowing object. You can't make out whether it's a planet, star, or maybe even a comet.

> listen

> listen

In the distance you can hear carol singers and a brass band, but they seem to be stopping and restarting the same song.
> e

> e

You are in a Town Square.

You can see a Choir Master.

You can go west, southeast, east, south, northeast or north.

There is a choir here and a brass band, attempting a rendition of "Hark The Herald Angels Sing!", but there is something not right about the relative tempo of the choir and the band. They keep stopping and retrying to get some flow. You can hear tuts and grumbles from the passing shoppers. The Choir Master looks exasperated and forlorn.

> x master

> x master

A tall man with a bushy black beard speckled with grey, wearing wire-frame glasses, a smart Dickensian style suit, greatcoat and sporting a caroler top hat.

He is repeatedly trying to get the choir and brass band to play in time together, but it's not going well. He looks fed up.

> talk to master

> talk to master

You catch the eye of the Choir Master and he wanders over to talk to you. "Hello my friend", he says, and shakes your hand. "We've having terrible trouble keeping in time with the band, their lead trumpeter player is at home sick." "Without him we're struggling to hear the melody and stay in time." "I suppose it's too late to find a replacement."
> x band

> x band

A brass band, but there is something wrong, they keep going out of time with the choir.
> e

> e

You are in a The Cross Keys Inn.

You can see a Jukebox, a Table Football, a Landlady, a Quiz Machine and James.

You can go west.

A great British pub, just like they used to be, all sticky carpets and wet tables. Thanks to the smoking ban there is a persistent scent of stale spilt beer and urinals.

> x James

> x James

Mid 30's, thin and scruffly dressed with a shock of bright ginger hair. He's wearing a battered rain coat, and a blue scarf.
> talk to James

> talk to James

"Hello" says James, "There's snow forcast!" he says with a grin.
> give stick to James

> give stick to James

"Oh nice one mate, that's really lovely, thank you!", Here take this, I saw they were selling out so I grabed you one. James hands you a copy of the Bumper Radio Times Christmas Special.
> x Bumper

> x Bumper

It's the 14 day christmas edition of the Radio Times. The front cover (which is already coming loose thanks to the woefully inadequate staples) features the stars of a Christmas edition of Strictly Celebrity Bake Off On Ice With Mrs Brown's Boys In The Jungle, at least with this guide you'll know exactly how to avoid catching it.
> talk to landlady

> talk to landlady

"Not enough money huh? Perhaps you can make yourself useful around here and I might sort you out with a drink."
> x jukebox

> x jukebox

A jukebox, and it's a nice one, a genuine Wurlitzer with actual vinyl singles inside. A label next to the coin slot reads "Insert coin to play'.
> x football

> x football

A big wooden table football game, 3 feet wide and 5 feet long. There are four wooden spindles on each side with handles on for controlling the players. It's free to play but unfortunately the wooden spindle on the red players goalie has snapped.
> unscrew broom

> unscrew broom

You unscrew the handle from the broom, you now have a wooden handle and a broom head.
> x head

> x head

A wooden broom head with plastic bristles.
> x handle

> x handle

A wooden cylindrical broom handle, 3 foot in length.
> use handle on table

> use handle on table

You unscrew the broken spindle, remove the goalie figure, attach it to the broom handle and screw it back into the table. It's fixed!

The landlady shouts across to you, "Thank you love, here have a drink for your troubles". She pours a pint of London Porter and places it on the bar. "And here take this, I had a load delivered as part of some promotion from the brewery." She hands you a corkscrew.

> take pint

> take pint

You pick it up.
> x pint

> x pint

A foaming pint of dark black London Porter with a white head. Lovely stuff!
> drink pint

> drink pint

You down it in several large draughts, it slips down like silk. You place the glass back on the bar, and supress a belch. The landlady take the glass and says, "Wow, you've really got a thirst on today, huh!".
> x corkscrew

> x corkscrew

A sharp corkscrew, the handle is in the shape of a bull's head.
> x machine

> x machine

A pub quiz machine, it has one free play left on it.
> play machine

> play machine

Answer 3 questions correct in a row to win.
